xample German   Schneider   and Hungarian   Szabo  . It is also very common among African Americans.","In some cases also an Americanized form of French   Terrien   ‘owner of a farmland’ or of its altered forms, such as   Therrien   and   Terrian  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Tayloe","meanings":["Altered form of English, Scottish, and Irish   Taylor  ."]},{"name":"Schneider","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Kurt, Hans, Otto, Franz, Erwin, Fritz, Dieter, Manfred, Heinz, Alois, Ewald, Helmut.","German and Jewish (Ashkenazic): occupational name for a tailor, literally ‘cutter’, from Middle High German <i>snīder</i>, German <i>Schneider</i>, Yiddish <i>shnayder</i>. The same term was sometimes used to denote a woodcutter. This surname is also established in many other parts of Europe, notably in France (Alsace and Lorraine), the Netherlands, Hungary, Poland, and Czechia. In Czechia, Slovakia, Croatia, and Slovenia it is also established in Slavicized forms (see 2 below). In part, <i>Schneider</i> is a Gottscheerish (i.e. Gottschee German) surname, originating from the Kočevsko region in Lower Carniola, Slovenia (see   Kocevar  ). Compare   Sneider   1,   Snider   1, and   Snyder   1.","Germanized form of Czech, Slovak, Croatian, and Slovenian <b>Šnajdr</b> or <b>Šnajder</b>, and Czech <b>Šneidr</b>, <b>Šneider</b>, <b>Šnejdr</b>, and <b>Šnejder</b>, surnames of German origin (see above)."]},{"name":"Tayler","meanings":["English: variant of   Taylor  ."]},{"name":"Tailor","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Pravin, Dilip, Mahesh, Sanjay, Kanchan, Kaushik, Manilal, Mohanlal, Navnit, Shailesh, Ajay, Alpana.","Indian (Gujarat and Mumbai): mainly Parsi occupational name from the English word <i>tailor</i>.","English: variant of   Taylor  ."]}]},{"name":"Ann","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Anne .  In the U.S. <i>Ann</i> is the more frequent spelling."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Martha","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, of Aramaic rather than Hebrew origin, meaning ‘lady’. It was borne by the sister of Lazarus and Mary of Bethany (John 11:1). According to Luke 10:38, when Jesus visited the house of Mary and Martha, Mary sat at his feet, listening to him, while Martha ‘was cumbered about much serving’, so that she complained to Jesus, ‘Lord, dost thou not care that my sister hath left me to serve alone?’ For this reason, the name <i>Martha</i> has always been associated with hard domestic work, as opposed to the contemplative life."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":74,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705202,"age":83,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705205,"age":94,"year":"1569","julianDay":2294126,"title":"State Lottery","description":"A State Lottery was recorded in 1569. The tickets were sold at St. Paul's Cathedral in London.","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"Ann Martha Taylor was born in 1475, in England. She married William Larkin in 1490, in Langley, Kent, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died about 1575, in her hometown, at the age of 101."},"et":{"1475–about 1575":"1475–umbes 1575","1470–Male":"1470–Surnud","1500–Male":"1500–Surnud","1475–1575":"1475–1575","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1490 to 1500":"1490","1500":"1500","1575":"1575","1475":"1475","about 1575":"umbes 1575","1470":"1470","1549":"1549","England":"England","Langley, Kent, England, United Kingdom":"Langley, Kent, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1475–about 1575":"1475–noin 1575","1470–Male":"1470–Kuollut","1500–Male":"1500–Kuollut","1475–1575":"1475–1575","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1490 to 1500":"1490","1500":"1500","1575":"1575","1475":"1475","about 1575":"noin 1575","1470":"1470","1549":"1549","England":"England","Langley, Kent, England, United Kingdom":"Langley, Kent, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1475–about 1575":"1475–environ 1575","1470–Male":"1470–Décédé","1500–Male":"1500–Décédé","1475–1575":"1475–1575","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1490 to 1500":"1490","1500":"1500","1575":"1575","1475":"1475","about 1575":"environ 1575","1470":"1470","1549":"1549","England":"Angleterre","Langley, Kent, England, United Kingdom":"Langley, Kent, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Ann Martha Taylor est née en 1475, à Angleterre. Elle a épousé William Larkin en 1490, à Langley, Kent, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni. Ils ont eu au moins 1 fils. Elle est décédée environ 1575, dans sa ville natale, à l’âge de 101 ans."},"de":{"1475–about 1575":"1475–um 1575","1470–Male":"1470–Verstorben","1500–Male":"1500–Verstorben","1475–1575":"1475–1575","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1490 to 1500":"1490","1500":"1500","1575":"1575","1475":"1475","about 1575":"um 1575","1470":"1470","1549":"1549","England":"England","Langley, Kent, England, United Kingdom":"Langley, Kent, England, United Kingdom","lifeSummary":"Ann Martha Taylor wurde 1475 in England geboren. Sie hat 1490 in Langley, Kent, En